{
  "slug": "count-non-adjacent-subsets-in-a-rooted-tree",
  "judge": "exact",
  "pattern": "Counting valid subsets by residue is a tree knapsack: combine each child's own count-by-residue distribution into the parent's, once assuming the parent is left out (children free to be in or out) and once assuming the parent is included (then no child may be), shifting the included case by the parent's own value.",
  "hints": [
    "Process the tree from the leaves upward; for each node, track two distributions indexed by remainder mod k: the count of valid subsets within its subtree when the node itself is excluded, and when it is included.",
    "When the node is excluded, its children are each free to be included or excluded, so combine every child's (included + excluded) distribution together by convolving their remainders mod k.",
    "When the node is included, none of its children may be included, so combine only the children's excluded distributions, then shift every remainder by the node's own value mod k; the final answer is the root's combined remainder-zero count, minus one for the empty subset."
  ],
  "constraints": [
    {
      "param": "parent",
      "kind": "int[]",
      "len": [
        1,
        1000
      ],
